<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-10-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-10-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="483" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4109</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Acting Secretary of the Navy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-10-25"><hi rend="italic">October 25,
                                1921</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">27403–340:5</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge your
                            letter of 18 October, 1921, (So 893.00/4021) relative to the furnishing
                            of naval escorts on foreign vessels in Chinese waters, and I beg to
                            inform you that <pb facs="0656" n="532" xml:id="pg_532"/> copies of the
                            correspondence in the premises have been furnished to the
                            Commander-in-Chief of the Asiatic Fleet with directions to be governed
                            by the spirit of your letter hereby acknowledged.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Thos. Washington</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>